<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n15016c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n15" href="#n15016c">N15 (VI.D.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n15all.htm#n15016c"> 16(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> quarry - -</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">As yet the assumption that any bridge was built at Dublin during King John&apos;s reign rests solely on the fact that permission was then given to destroy one bridge and to build another, whilst we have records to prove that both before and considerably after that period there was a bridge at Dublin called &ldquo;the <mark>Bridge of the Ostmen</mark>.&rdquo; In a grant to Ralph la Hore in 1236, the land is described &ldquo;in capite pontis Ostmannorum.&rdquo; The name is repeated in a grant to William de Nottingham so late as 1284, which describes a stone tower as being &ldquo;juxta pontem Ostmannorum,&rdquo; and as these records also refer to &ldquo;the gate of the Ostmen,&rdquo; to &ldquo;<mark>the old quarry of the Ostmen</mark>&rdquo; (&ldquo;a veteri quadrivio Ostmanorum&rdquo;), &c., there are grounds for supposing that the works so denominated had been executed by the Ostmen, and were not works thus called from proximity to the suburb of Ostmantown. <br>218.n3: &ldquo;Know all men that we, the citizens of Dublin, have by this our charter granted and confirmed to Ralph Hore and William Russell, our fellow citizens, a meadow of ours extending in length from <mark>the Old Quarry of the Ostmen</mark> to Kylmehanok&rdquo;. <small> Charles Haliday, <a name="SKD2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SKD2"><cite title="source">The Scandinavian Kingdom of Dublin</cite></a>, 2nd ed. (1884) 217</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c15192c" href="c15all.htm#c15192c">VI.C.15:192(c)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
